<section class="intro-section mb-12">
    <h3 id="overview">Overview</h3>
    <p>{{ docs.intro | safe }}</p>
</section>
<section class="docs-section">
    <h3 id="specifications" class="text-xl font-bold mb-6">Specifications</h3>
    <div class="standards-stack">
        {% for spec in docs.specs %}
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <div class="mb-3">
                <h4 id="spec-title" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">{{ spec.title }}</h4>
                {% if spec.subtitle %}
                    <span class="text-sm text-gray-500 font-normal">{{ spec.subtitle }}</span>
                {% endif %}
            </div>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4 flex-grow">{{ spec.description }}</p>
            {% if spec.note %}
            <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-400 p-3 mb-4 text-xs text-blue-800">
                <strong>Note:</strong> {{ spec.note }}
            </div>
            {% endif %}
            {% if spec.code %}
            <div class="mt-auto">
                <we-code-view><pre class="bg-gray-800 text-gray-100 p-3 rounded text-xs overflow-x-auto font-mono mb-0"><code>{{ spec.code }}</code></pre></we-code-view>
            </div>
            {% endif %}
        </div>
        {% endfor %}
    </div>
</section>
<section class="docs-section mt-12">
    <h3 id="protocol-custom-elements-manifest" class="text-xl font-bold mb-6">Protocol — Custom Elements Manifest</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
        A block's machine-readable <strong>structural contract</strong> is expressed as a
        <a href="https://github.com/webcomponents/custom-elements-manifest" class="text-blue-600 underline">Custom Elements Manifest</a>
        (<code>custom-elements.json</code>, schema <code>2.1.0</code>) — the de-facto multi-vendor manifest describing a
        custom element's tag, attributes, properties, events, slots, CSS custom properties and parts. WE
        <strong>adopts the open spec</strong> rather than minting a bespoke format: this is the single escapable lock —
        the same manifest is consumed unchanged by api-viewer, Storybook, VS Code custom-data and JetBrains web-types,
        so a project can leave WE without losing its component metadata. It is the <em>structural</em> half of the block
        protocol; the <em>behavioral</em> half is the block's <code>block-description.njk</code> (Open UI / WAI-ARIA APG).
    </p>
    <ul class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4 list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
        <li><strong>Derived, never hand-authored.</strong> <code>npm run gen:cem</code>
            (<code>scripts/gen-cem.mjs</code>) projects the block-protocol fields a <code>blocks.json</code> entry
            already carries — <code>events</code>/<code>exports</code>, paired with
            <code>implementsIntent</code>/<code>traits</code>/<code>webStandards</code> — into the CEM shape. Output is
            deterministic (sorted by block id, no timestamp), so the committed <code>custom-elements.json</code> can't
            drift and a re-run over unchanged blocks is a no-op diff.</li>
        <li><strong>No fabricated tags.</strong> A block is emitted as a CEM <code>custom-element</code> declaration
            (<code>customElement: true</code> + <code>tagName</code>) only when it carries an explicit
            <code>tagName</code>; otherwise it is a plain <code>class</code> declaration
            (<code>registryName</code> is a DI-registry class name, never a tag).</li>
        <li><strong>Spec-valid core.</strong> WE-specific fields ride under a namespaced
            <code>x-webeverything</code> extension so the core manifest stays valid for external tooling.</li>
        <li><strong>One seam, many consumers.</strong> Feeds the props-table block, the Technical Configurator args
            panel, and autodocs (the Web Docs catalog surface, #627). Discoverable via the
            <code>package.json "customElements"</code> field.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-400 p-3 mb-4 text-xs text-blue-800">
        <strong>Forward-compatible:</strong> as blocks gain structured attribute / slot / CSS-API fields, the same
        pipeline emits a richer per-element manifest — no schema change, a status flip from <code>draft</code>.
    </div>
</section>
<section class="docs-section mt-12">
    <h3 id="derivation-source" class="text-xl font-bold mb-6">Dimension — Derivation source</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
        <em>Where the catalog manifest's content comes from</em> is a <strong>supported dimension</strong>, not a
        mandated mechanism (ruled in <a href="/backlog/706-generate-fui-s-block-catalog-from-a-derived-manifest-and-rend/" class="text-blue-600 underline">#706</a>).
        Both an authored manifest and an implementation scan are coherent end-states — the right choice depends on
        whether the implementation carries enough annotated metadata to derive quality summaries — so by the
        fork-existence test it is an axis to support, not a call to decide. Every source emits the <strong>same CEM
        contract</strong>, so downstream consumers (props table, Technical Configurator, autodocs) never see the difference.
    </p>
    <ul class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4 list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
        <li><strong>Authored → CEM (the default / reference).</strong> The curated <code>blocks.json</code> metadata
            (summary / type / protocol / <code>weSpecPath</code>) projected into the manifest by
            <code>npm run gen:cem</code> — the path documented above. Default because authored summaries are
            human-quality where a raw source scan emits only thin tag/member data with no prose.</li>
        <li><strong>Impl-scan / CEM-from-source (opt-in).</strong> A custom-elements-manifest analyzer run over the
            implementation source, emitting the same contract. Complete by construction (no entry can be forgotten),
            but only as rich as the JSDoc / decorator annotations the source carries — opt-in for implementations
            that are annotated.</li>
        <li><strong>Hybrid.</strong> Scan for structure (tags, members, slots), author the prose summaries — the two
            sources merged into one manifest.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-400 p-3 mb-4 text-xs text-blue-800">
        <strong>Completeness is source-independent:</strong> a build-time gate asserts the manifest covers every
        implemented block family regardless of how it was derived — a scanned manifest is complete by construction;
        an authored one is held complete by the gate (#706 invariant).
    </div>
</section>
